### Common Mistakes in Async JavaScript Functions
=====================================================

Async JavaScript functions can be tricky to work with, and there are several common mistakes that developers make when using them. Here are some of the most common mistakes and how to avoid them:

### 1. Not Handling Rejection

When using `async/await`, it's essential to handle rejections properly. If an error occurs in an `async` function, it will be thrown as an unhandled rejection, which can cause the program to crash.

```javascript
// Bad practice
async function example() {
  const data = await fetch('https://example.com/api/data');
  console.log(data);
}

// Good practice
async function example() {
  try {
    const data = await fetch('https://example.com/api/data');
    console.log(data);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error:', error);
  }
}
```

### 2. Not Checking for Null or Undefined Values

When working with async functions, it's easy to forget to check if a value is null or undefined before trying to use it.

